AGE¶

Histogram and Boxplot for Age¶

  1. It shows average age of an insurer
  2. It shows the frequency of age for the insurers
In [13]:
#import warning to supress in out
import warnings
#supress warning 
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
#set plot style
sns.set(style="ticks")
#set x equals to column of our interest which is age here
x=dataset['age']
#create figure f, boxplot and histogram in single chart        
f, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, 
                                    gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (.15, .85)})
#set input in boxplot
sns.boxplot(x, ax=ax_box)
#set input in histogram
sns.distplot(x, ax=ax_hist)
ax_box.set(yticks=[])
#plot the histogram
sns.despine(ax=ax_hist)
#plot the  boxplot 
sns.despine(ax=ax_box, left=True)

Exploratory Analysis¶

Sex¶

Bar chart¶

  1. It shows the % of each gender served by axis insurance
In [17]:
#set chart style
sns.set(style="whitegrid")
#create figure from plt
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
#get the size of dataset
total = float(len(dataset))
#create chart ax with column sex and datasource equals to dataset
ax = sns.countplot(x="sex", data=dataset)
#calculate the percentage and put it on the top of bars with below code
for p in ax.patches:
    #how the percentage should be formated
    percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height()/total)
    # % position in X
    x = p.get_x() + 0.4
    # % position in Y
    y = p.get_height()+5
    #put percentage on chart
    ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y),ha='center')
#plot the chart
plt.show()

Statistical Analysis¶

Prove (or disprove) that the medical claims made by the people who smoke is greater than those who don't?¶

Independent T Test¶

Null Hypothesis--> H0 = "charges has no effect on smoking"¶

Alternate hypothesis--> H1 = "charges has effect on smoking"¶

In [35]:
#code performs the T-Test
#import independent t test
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind
#create category of smokers 
cat1 = dataset[dataset['smoker']=='yes']
#create category of non smokers
cat2 = dataset[dataset['smoker']=='no']
#mean claims by smokers
print(cat1['charges'].mean())
#mean claims by non-smokers
print(cat2['charges'].mean())
#apply independent t test
print(ttest_ind(cat1['charges'], cat2['charges']))
#plot smoker vs charges
ax = sns.boxplot(x="smoker", y="charges", data=dataset)

32050.23183153285
8434.268297856199
Ttest_indResult(statistic=46.664921172723716, pvalue=8.271435842177219e-283)

Statistical Analysis¶

Prove (or disprove) with statistical evidence that the BMI of females is different from that of males.¶

Independent T Test¶

Null Hypothesis--> H0 = "Gender has no effect on BMI"¶

Alternate hypothesis--> H1 = "Gender has effect on BMI"¶

In [36]:
#code performs the T-Test
#import independent t test
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind
#create category of male 
cat1 = dataset[dataset['sex']=='male']
#create category of female
cat2 = dataset[dataset['smoker']=='no']
#apply independent t test
print(ttest_ind(cat1['bmi'], cat2['bmi']))
#plot bmi vs sex
ax = sns.boxplot(x="bmi", y="sex", orient="h", data=dataset)

Ttest_indResult(statistic=0.974043464681153, pvalue=0.330170504024037)

Is the proportion of smokers significantly different across different regions?¶

Null Hypothesis--> H0 = "Smokers are effected by region"¶

Alternate hypothesis--> H1 = "Smokers are not effected by region"¶

In [37]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency
data_crosstab = pd.crosstab(dataset['smoker'],
                            dataset['region'], 
                               margins = False)
print(chi2_contingency(data_crosstab))
ax = sns.boxplot(x="region", y="charges", hue='smoker',data=dataset)

(7.34347776140707, 0.06171954839170547, 3, array([[257.65022422, 258.44544096, 289.45889387, 258.44544096],
       [ 66.34977578,  66.55455904,  74.54110613,  66.55455904]]))

Is the mean BMI of women with no children, one child, and two children the same?¶

Null Hypothesis--> H0 = "Average BMI of female with 0,1,2 children is same"¶

Alternate hypothesis--> H1 = ""Average BMI of female with 0,1,2 children is not same""¶

In [38]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency
data_crosstab = pd.crosstab(dataset[dataset['sex']=='female']['bmi'].mean,
                            dataset['children'],
                               margins = False)
print(chi2_contingency(data_crosstab.iloc[:,0:3]))
ax = sns.boxplot(x="bmi", y="sex", hue='children', data=dataset)

(0.0, 1.0, 0, array([[574., 324., 240.]]))
